    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-07-05T03:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-07-05T03:00:00-05:00" n="824"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d824">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.0011 European War 1939/12820: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in France</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Leahy</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-07-05T10:00:00+02:00"
                            >July 5, 1941—10 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 1:55 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>808. Embassy’s telegram 802, July 3, 4 p.m.<note n="18" xml:id="d824fn18">
                        <ref target="frus1941v05#pg_522">Vol. <hi rend="smallcaps">v</hi>, p.
                            522</ref>.</note> Ostrorog<note n="18a" xml:id="d824fn18a">Stanislas
                        Ostrorog, of the French Foreign Office.</note> informs us that a telegram
                    has now been received from Arsene-Henry indicating that probably a decision was
                    reached at the recent Imperial Council meeting in Tokyo in favor of a move
                    against Russia. The so-called northern party seems to have “won out,” according
                    to Henry, and has been strongly supported by German influence at Tokyo. The
                    German motives he reported are threefold: first, for obvious military <pb
                        facs="1004" n="996" xml:id="pg_996"/> reasons, to create further
                    difficulties for Russia; second, in the hope of bringing about a clash between
                    the United States and Japan; and third, because Germany has no desire to see the
                    Japanese move south toward the Dutch East Indies, an area with respect to which
                    the Nazis have aspirations of their own. Ostrorog remarked that obviously
                    Germany “did not recognize the Nanking regime for nothing” and some commitment
                    for a move against Russia may well have been obtained from Japan.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Leahy</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
